[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_5UmvJitc81NUE5CWVrbhNeJU|fc_0546e149f87d035b0169fa51b2091481969332b639aa78d05a", "toolName": "read", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "/*\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\n *\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\n */\npackage com_google_inject.guice;\n\npublic final class DenyGuiceFinalizerSystemClassLoader extends ClassLoader {\n    private static final String FINALIZER_CLASS_NAME = \"com.google.inject.internal.util.$Finalizer\";\n\n    public DenyGuiceFinalizerSystemClassLoader(ClassLoader parent) {\n        super(parent);\n    }\n\n    @Override\n    protected Class<?> loadClass(String name, boolean resolve) throws ClassNotFoundException {\n        if (isGuiceFinalizerClass(name)) {\n            throw new ClassNotFoundException(name);\n        }\n        return super.loadClass(name, resolve);\n    }\n\n    private static boolean isGuiceFinalizerClass(String name) {\n        return name.equals(FINALIZER_CLASS_NAME) || name.startsWith(FINALIZER_CLASS_NAME + \"$\");\n    }\n}\n"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1778012594574}}
[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering system class loaders**\n\nI'm thinking about the system class loader and how it can be nested. The JVM can load nested classes from bootclasspath JARs, which can have names containing a dollar sign ($). However, tests typically don't allow $ in file names or test class names, which makes things a bit tricky. Maybe helper classes that aren't test classes could be okay, but it seems the earlier issues were related to the bootclasspath. We decided to simplify things by separating them.\n\n**Clarifying Java test classes**\n\nI’m thinking about how to avoid generating extra Java files by using a nested class and implementing append. There’s something about the jvmArgs splitting, and I realized that the system class loader's naming convention includes a \"$\", while helper classes don’t have \"Test.\" It looks like I might not be generating a test correctly. However, putting helper classes into their own Java files might not violate the rule of keeping dynamic-access classes in dedicated test files. I prefer folding helpers into one test file as a nested public static class, though. Got it!\n\n**Exploring nested class loading**\n\nI'm reflecting on the previous failure of the nested custom loader because it didn’t implement 'append.' I see that removing the Deny... file and rewriting tests with a nested URLClassLoader could work if I update the build.gradle to include the inner class, even with jvmArgs splitting. I'm also pondering the visibility of the class to the bootstrap. Should I load both the test class and inner class in the boot jar to be safe? But that might create duplicates in JUnit!\n\n**Addressing custom loader issues**\n\nIt might be okay, but I find it a bit strange. I realize that a custom system loader class can be top-level and not just for testing, allowing for one extra helper if necessary. A simpler fix could be editing the helper 